definitions.meaning: If you wear in smth such as a pair of shoes, you wear them until they fit you better and are more comfortable
examples: It’s always so painful wearing in new shoes.
I could hear my mother telling me to wrap up warm.

definitions.meaning: Arrive and register at a hotel or airport
examples: Please check in at least an hour before departure.
We checked out at noon.
Please take out the trash before the whole house starts to smell.
Let me take you out for dinner.

definitions.meaning: Adopt a responsibility or duty from someone else
examples: He will take over the job permanently when the accountant retires.

definitions.meaning: Buy out the ownership of a business
examples: Facebook took over Instagram several years ago.
The general took over the country after the revolution.

definitions.meaning: Annex a territory by conquest or invasion
examples: Ancient Rome took over lands throughout the known world.
She took to swimming like a fish.
She took to smoking after the accident.
I’ll take you through how to set up a web server.

definitions.meaning: Move from being on top of (something) to not being on top of it
examples: Get off your chair and help me.
You get off the train at the third stop.

definitions.meaning: Stop using a phone or computer
examples: Can you get off the phone, please? I need your help.

definitions.meaning: Leave work earlier or later than usual
examples: If I can get off early tomorrow, I’ll give you a ride home.

definitions.meaning: Stop touching or interfering with something or someone
examples: Don’t touch me – get off!

definitions.meaning: Begin a sexual relationship with smb
examples: I’d like to get off with him after the party.
The vandal got off easy, with only a fine.
If I wake up during the night, I cannot get off again.
Please get on the bus as quickly as possible.
She’s getting on very well at school.
Time is getting on.
My parents are visibly getting on a bit these days.
I wish you and I could learn to get on.
The dishes need washing, the floor needs vacuuming, laundry needs folding. Get on it!
I have to get on with my task.
In case of fire, get out by the nearest exit.
Somehow the secret got out.

definitions.meaning: Spend free time out of the house
examples: You work too hard. You should get out more.
This detergent will get most household stains out.
I only cheat so I can get out of doing work.
I’m trying to get over my fear of flying.
I’m having problems getting over a bad cold.
She was in love with me for 10 years, and still hasn’t got over the fact that the feeling wasn’t mutual.
I want to get rid of your influence over my life!
Military training was hard, but I got through it
She got through her book this morning!
The call wouldn’t get through no matter how many times I tried.
I feel I’m not getting through to some of the kids in my class.

definitions.meaning: Reach a stage in a competition
examples: She got through to the final round of interviews.
I’ll call you when I get to the railway station.
And you get to be the team’s captain!

definitions.meaning: Affect in a bad way; upset or annoy
examples: This job is really getting to me. I don’t know how much longer I’ll last.

definitions.meaning: Track down and find smb, and threaten them
examples: He’s refusing to tell the truth. I think the government got to him.
We used to get together with our friends every Friday at this cafe.
I’m having difficulty getting up the stairs.
I didn’t get up until midday.
Get up and clean this mess!

definitions.meaning: Do something, especially something that you should not do
examples: Recently he’s been getting up to all sorts of mischief.
The bad news took us aback.

definitions.meaning: Start doing an activity (usually a hobby)
examples: I’ve taken up knitting.
Let’s take this up with the manager.

definitions.meaning: Fill a lot of space or time
examples: The English homework takes up most of my weekend.

definitions.meaning: Accept smb’s offer and remember it when the time comes
examples: Shall we take them up on their offer to help us move?
